-- Sub-Saharan African Stocks: Housing Finance of Kenya, Innodis Are Active
-- B y   E r i c   O m b o k
-- 2010-09-28T14:45:08Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-09-28/sub-saharan-african-stocks-housing-finance-of-kenya-innodis-are-active.html
The  Nigerian Stock Exchange All-
Share Index  snapped the longest streak of declines since June,
rising 0.1 percent to 22,429.09 by the 1 p.m. close in Lagos.  Mauritius’s  SEMDEX Index  snapped three days of declines,
rising 0.6 percent to 1,773.7 by the 1:30 p.m. close in Port
Louis. Kenya’s  All-Share Index  rose for the first day in four,
climbing 0.1 percent to 82.81 by the 3 p.m. close in Nairobi.  Namibia’s  FTSE/Namibia Overall Index  climbed 0.2 percent to
792.38 by 2:55 p.m. in Windhoek, a second day of increases.  The  Ghana Stock Exchange All-Share Index  fell for a third
day, the longest streak of losses since July 22, dropping 0.3
percent to 6,631.29 by the 1 p.m. close in Accra.  The following shares rose or fell in sub-Saharan Africa,
excluding South Africa. Stock symbols are in parentheses.  Housing Finance Co. Ltd.  (HFCL KN), Kenya’s only publicly
traded mortgage company, climbed for a second day, gaining 25
cents, or 1 percent, to 26.25 shillings. The stock advanced on
bets the company’s 5 billion-shilling ($61.8 million) bond sale
to increase lending to its customers will be oversubscribed,
Genghis Capital Ltd. analyst  Renaldo D’souza  said by phone from
Nairobi.  Innodis Ltd.  (HWF MP), a Mauritian food manufacturer, rose
0.1 rupee, or 0.3 percent, to 29.4 rupees. Net income for the
year through June increased 10 percent to 133.1 million rupees
as revenue advanced, the company said in a statement published
in l’Express newspaper today. The company declared a dividend of
1.4 rupees a share.  To contact the reporter on this story:
